04699nam a22007455i 9780231550628DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021017228  a97802315506287 a10.7312/loug194042doi  a(DE-B1597)617399  a(OCoLC)1256588100  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHT175 7aSOC0260302bisacsh04a307.3/41609732231 aLoughran, Kevin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aParks for Profit :bSelling Nature in the City /cKevin Loughran. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2022] 4c©2021  a1 online resource :b20 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tI INTRODUCTION -- t1 SOMETIME IN 2009 -- t2 VARIETIES OF URBAN CRISIS -- tII GROWTH MACHINES IN THE GARDEN -- t3 “THE YUPPIE EXPRESS” -- t4 “NO MORE BAKE SALES, MAN” -- t5 “A PIECE OF CRUD” -- t6 PARKS FOR PROFIT OR FOR PEOPLE? -- tIII GARDENS IN THE MACHINE -- t7 DEFECTIVE LANDSCAPES -- t8 IMBRICATED SPACES -- t9 CONSTRUCTING ENVIRONMENTAL AUTHENTICITY -- t10 SPATIAL PRACTICES AND SOCIAL CONTROL -- tIV CONCLUSION -- t11 AFTER THE HIGH LINE -- t12 ABOLISH, DECOLONIZE, ROT -- tNOTES -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA new kind of city park has emerged in the early twenty-first century. Postindustrial parks transform the derelict remnants of an urban past into distinctive public spaces that meld repurposed infrastructure, wild-looking green space, and landscape architecture. For their proponents, they present an opportunity to turn disused areas into neighborhood anchors, with a host of environmental and community benefits. Yet there are clear economic motives as well—successful parks have helped generate billions of dollars of city tax revenues and real estate development.Kevin Loughran explores the High Line in New York, the Bloomingdale Trail/606 in Chicago, and Buffalo Bayou Park in Houston to offer a critical perspective on the rise of the postindustrial park. He reveals how elites deploy the popularity and seemingly benign nature of parks to achieve their cultural, political, and economic goals. As urban economies have become restructured around finance, real estate, tourism, and cultural consumption, parks serve as civic shields for elite-oriented investment. Tracing changing ideas about cities and nature and underscoring the centrality of race and class, Loughran argues that postindustrial parks aestheticize past disinvestment while serving as green engines of gentrification.A wide-ranging investigation of the political, cultural, and economic forces shaping park development, Parks for Profit reveals the social inequalities at the heart of today’s new urban landscape.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aGentrificationzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aParkszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aSocial stratificationzUnited StatesvCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aBloomingdale Trail/606.  aBuffalo Bayou Park.  aChicago.  aHigh Line.  aHouston.  aNew York City.  acity parks.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073907740uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/loug1940440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231550628423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231550628/original  a978-3-11-073907-7  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK